By Katie Kaminski
Staff‘ Writer

Theme park audition
teams are coming to cam-
pus, and they’re looking for
you.

Around this time each
year, teams of theme park
auditioners and park repre-
sentatives tour the nations’
college campuses searching
for talented students to fill a
variety of positions including
dancers, singers, instrumen-
talists, magicians, comedians
and costumed characters.

Although parks generally
employ anyone over 16
years old, college students
make up a large portion of
many theme park payrolls.
For example, of the 4,500
employees at Kings Island a
“huge part” are college stu-
dents, said Terry Brinkman,

employment supervisor for
the Cincinnati, Ohio, theme
park.

Theme park stages are the
ideal place for performers to
display their talents while
polishing their skills, accord-
ing to park representatives.

“A lot of our singers have
gone on to perform on
cruise ships, and they’ve
even gone to New York to
Radio City Music Hall,”
Brinkman said.

Theme parks are a great
place for aspiring performers
to begin. Brinkman also said
that many performers get
their first experiences in
entertaining live audiences
on theme park stages.

Not everyone is suited for
these jobs, however. Parks
have very specific qualities
they look for in applicants.

