Let them eat lobster

It is one of the most famous lines ever spoken. Admonishing
in the wealth and prestige of her position, “Let them eat cake,”
said Marie Antoinette to her French peasants. The rest of the
story is history. Antoinette had her head chopped off, and the
peasants revolted. France was to never have a monarchy again.

Turning the pages of the calendar forward to Jan. 25, 1992;
Student Government Board President Jacob Brody and his
trusty sidekick Ted Schroeder echoed these sentiments. In
comparison to Antoinette, only the means by which Brody

, assumed power was different, and the phrasing of the state-

ment slightly less definitive. “Can’t we just put it behind us?”
asked Schroeder, referring to the infamous SGB retreat in
Nemacolin Woodlands. Calling for Brody’s head is still a bit
premature. But the restraint is shaky and a revolution surely
awaits.

But for now, political turmoil lurks and President Brody has
yet to answer many of the questions surrounding the trip. Such
as how are students going to be reimbursed for the reckless
spending of their money, money that wasn’t allocated in the
first place?

Well there is one more question for him to ponder. Is it pos-
sible to put something behind you, when it has not even been
placed in front? Last night at the SGB meeting, SGB President
Jacob Brody and members of the board met attempted to put
the $9,000 retreat behind them. It seems they only re—ignited
the flame.

The voting blocks were very telling. There were four mem-
bers who voted for the allocation of the funds, two who voted
against it and two who abstained. Anthony Moody expressed
his support of it by explaining that it wasn’t a moral issue and
Schroeder added that since the money was already spent it
was time to move on. To welp on board members may not be
fair since they didn‘t vote on the retreat. However, it is impor-
tant to note that by voting in favor of the funding, they are
granting legitimacy to Brody’s actions.

Given these situations, why didn’t they vote to deny the
funding if it didn’t matter anyway? Clearly, students are out-
raged, and if it isn’t a moral issue then what is it? Perhaps we
should have let Richard Nixon serve out his second term in the
White House. Who cares that he stole the tapes? We sho_uld
have probably just put that behind us as well.

Brody has met with a barrage of criticism surrounding the
trip. It was unnecessary and excessive. Not only that, but he
also spent money that was not allocated to him. Perhaps worse
than the trip itself is the fact that Brody has failed to explain
himself to the student community at large. Two weeks ago
Brody was phoned by The Pitt News and was offered the
